<hl>
<seg id=1> Japanese Prime Minister Wishes Kiichi Miyazawa to Remain in Office to Fullfil Economic Recovery Plan </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (Reuters, Tokyo) Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa yesterday was pressed to remain in office. </seg>
<seg id=3> He declared last week that he had the intention of resignation. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Miyazawa's leave or stay also shadowed the united government composed of Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's Liberal Democratic Party and Ichiro Ozawa's Liberal Party. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> After the divergence of senior officials' views on whether the Liberal Party's cabinet seats were agreed on came to a head, the instability of the united government appeared. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> It is widespread outside that after Miyazawa's resignation, Byota, General Director of Liberal Party will replace him. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Last Friday Miyazawa expressed that he might resign before the end of this year but did not say the exact date. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> He said at the press conference, "I can't say when." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> It is estimated that he will remain as the Finance Minister until the Congress' two-week special session is over. </seg>
<seg id=10> The Congress session will close on December 14. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> Keizo Obuchi's deputy cabinet secretary Suzuki told NHK TV Station that he believes the Prime Minister wishes 79-year-old Kiyazawa to continue. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> Suzuki said, "I think (Obuchi) privatelly wishes him to continue to fulfil his economic recovery plan." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=13> Obuchi will talk to Miyazawa face to face. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=14> He said, "concerning his capabilities, it is not easy to find another one to take his place. </seg>
<seg id=15> I myself hope that he remains to make efforts to rejuvenate our national economy." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=16> Keizo Obuchi's public comment on Miyazawa's intention to resign is that he has read the related report and he would like to talk to the Finance Minister. </seg>
</p>
